Reasoning: 
- cs.LG (Machine Learning): The paper is primarily focused on developing a method for training kernel approximation methods that generalize well under a memory budget. 
- cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): The paper proposes a new method for kernel approximation that can be useful in various AI applications. 
- cs.CV (Computer Vision): The paper demonstrates the effectiveness of the proposed method on benchmark datasets commonly used in computer vision. 
- cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms): The paper proposes a low-precision quantization method for random Fourier features to build a high-rank approximation under a memory budget, which can be of interest to researchers in data structures and algorithms. 
- cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing): The paper proposes a method for kernel approximation that can be useful in neural network training, which falls under the scope of neural and evolutionary computing.
